title: Socio-economic factors affecting healthcare in Missouri
author: Author A. B.
summary: This paper analyzes the impact of multiple socio-economic indicators in Missouri — including income, employment, and housing stability — on public health outcomes such as chronic disease prevalence, ER visits, and preventative service uptake.

statistical_analysis.findings: Regions within Missouri with limited access to primary care and higher socioeconomic stress reported a 17–24% increase in ER visits. Preventative care usage was notably lower in low-income rural counties (p < 0.01).

policy_implication: The findings suggest a need for targeted policy actions in Missouri, including expanding Medicaid access, boosting public transit to healthcare centers, and launching education-based health awareness campaigns in underserved areas.
references: Missouri Department of Health Annual Reports

statistical_analysis.findings: Regions within New Mexico with limited access to primary care and higher socioeconomic stress reported a 17–24% increase in ER visits. Preventative care usage was notably lower in low-income rural counties (p < 0.01).

policy_implication: The findings suggest a need for targeted policy actions in New Mexico, including expanding Medicaid access, boosting public transit to healthcare centers, and launching education-based health awareness campaigns in underserved areas.
references: New Mexico Department of Health Annual Reports
